# Infrastructure Conventions

Coding standards and conventions for all infrastructure code in the medinovai-deploy repository.

## Terraform Conventions

### Module Structure
Every Terraform module must follow this structure:
```
modules/<name>/
â”śâ”€â”€ main.tf           # Resource definitions
â”śâ”€â”€ variables.tf      # Input variables with descriptions + validation
â”śâ”€â”€ outputs.tf        # Exported values for downstream modules
â”śâ”€â”€ versions.tf       # Required providers + version constraints
â””â”€â”€ README.md         # Module documentation
```

### Naming
- Resources: `<provider>_<resource>` with name `"${var.environment}-${var.project}-<purpose>"`
- Variables: snake_case, descriptive, always include `description` and `type`
- Outputs: snake_case, match the resource attribute name where possible
- Tags: Every resource must have `Environment`, `Project`, `ManagedBy=terraform`, `CostCenter`

### Variables
- Always set `description` for every variable
- Use `validation` blocks for critical inputs (CIDR ranges, instance types, etc.)
- Never use default values for secrets or environment-specific values
- Use `sensitive = true` for any variable containing credentials

### State Management
- Remote state in S3 with DynamoDB locking
- One state file per environment per module layer
- State bucket naming: `medinovai-terraform-state-<account-id>-<region>`
- Lock table naming: `medinovai-terraform-lock`
- Enable versioning and encryption on state bucket

### Security
- Never use `*` in IAM policies â€” always least privilege
- Security groups default deny; explicit allow only
- Encryption at rest for all data stores (RDS, S3, EBS, EFS)
- Encryption in transit (TLS 1.2+ everywhere)
- No public subnets for data stores or application services

## Kubernetes Conventions

### Manifests
- Use Kustomize (not Helm) for environment overlays
- Base manifests in `infra/kubernetes/base/` and `infra/kubernetes/services/<name>/`
- Environment-specific patches in `infra/kubernetes/overlays/<env>/`

### Resource Requirements
- Every pod MUST have CPU and memory requests AND limits
- Every deployment MUST have readiness and liveness probes
- Every production deployment MUST have a PodDisruptionBudget
- HorizontalPodAutoscaler for all stateless services

### Naming
- Namespaces: `medinovai-<domain>` (e.g., `medinovai-services`, `medinovai-data`)
- Services: match the service manifest name
- ConfigMaps: `<service>-config`
- Secrets: `<service>-secrets`

### Security
- Default deny NetworkPolicies per namespace
- Non-root containers (runAsNonRoot: true)
- Read-only root filesystem where possible
- No privileged containers
- ServiceAccount per service (no default SA)

## Docker Conventions

### Base Images
- Always pin exact versions (no `:latest`)
- Use multi-stage builds (builder + runtime)
- Non-root USER in every Dockerfile
- HEALTHCHECK instruction in every Dockerfile
- Minimize image size (no dev tools in production images)

### Image Tagging
- `<registry>/<service>:<git-sha>` for traceability
- `<registry>/<service>:<semver>` for release versions
- Never overwrite existing tags

## Script Conventions

### Bash Scripts
- Start with `#!/usr/bin/env bash` and `set -euo pipefail`
- Accept `--dry-run` flag for all destructive operations
- Use consistent logging format with timestamps
- Exit with meaningful codes (0=success, 1=error, 2=needs-human)
- Support `--json` output for machine consumption
- Checkpoint long operations for resumability

### Python Scripts
- Accept `--json-in` on stdin, output JSON to stdout
- Include `if __name__ == "__main__"` guard
- Use `argparse` for CLI arguments
- Log to stderr, results to stdout
